    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nwhen opening an existing buffer using `vim.api.nvim_open_term(0, {})` the new terminal buffer has an extra newline at the end.\n\n## motivation\nI want to open my tmux scrollback in neovim with a keybind, and have it look exactly the same as it did before opening neovim.\n\nThe extra newline makes my view one line off from how it look before opening neovim. \n\nThis is the lua code I run after opening the scrollback file:\n```lua\n  vim.o.laststatus = 0\n  vim.o.cmdheight = 0\n\n  vim.wo.number = false\n  vim.wo.relativenumber = false\n  vim.wo.statuscolumn = ''\n  vim.wo.signcolumn = 'no'\n  vim.opt.listchars = { space = ' ' }\n\n  local buf = vim.api.nvim_get_current_buf()\n  vim.api.nvim_open_term(buf, {})\n\n  vim.keymap.set('n', 'q', '<cmd>q<cr>', { silent = true, buffer = buf })\n  vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd('TextChanged', { buffer = buf, command = 'normal! G$' })\n  vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd('TermEnter', { buffer = buf, command = 'stopinsert' })\n```\n\nMy workaround for now is to move the cursor and scroll position one line up in the script.\nThis is not ideal because when I want to go back to the bottom (using `G`) after moving around a bit I go to the trailing newline instead of the last line of the scrollback.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nnvim --clean\n200i test\\n<ESC>\ndd\n:lua vim.api.nvim_open_term(0 ,{})\n:set nu\nG\n\nYou can now see that the cursor is at line 201 instead of 200\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nNo newline would be inserted at the end.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.12.0\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno (because there is no nvim_open_term :)\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux 6.19.10-203.nobara.fc43.x86_64\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\ntmux 3.5a\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\ntmux-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nUsing https://github.com/mordechaihadad/bob",
